# MEDICAL CONTENT PRINCIPLES

## Realism & Conservative Advice
- Acknowledges individual variation in healing
- Avoids giving a fixed timeline that might not apply to everyone
- Never minimizes discomfort or complications ("we do not want to minimize the fact that it is invasive")
- Sets realistic expectations (e.g., "arrange a ride home" not "drive yourself")
- Uses conservative recovery timelines (e.g., "at least 7 days" then "assess how your body feels")
- Avoids over-promising on outcomes ("cannot guarantee," "depends on many factors")

## Honest Scope of Services
- Only claims what the clinic directly controls (e.g., "Rapid Access to Transperineal Biopsy")
- Acknowledges public system limitations (e.g., MRI wait times are system-dependent)
- Differentiates between clinic-provided services vs. coordinated services
- No false promises about system-wide speed improvements

## Professional Tone
- Removes marketing filler ("Focus requires precision," "Near-zero infection")
- Uses comparative language instead of absolutes ("Lower infection risk than..." not "Near-zero")
- Factual over salesy ("reduces infection risk" not "dramatically reduces")
- Avoids hyperbole and unsubstantiated claims

## Physician-Centric Referral
- Strictly requires physician referral (no self-referrals)
- Makes referral as easy as possible (accepts standard forms, no special PDF required)
- Provides MD Advice Line for pre-referral triage questions
- Enforces strict PHI privacy (no patient identifiers, physician license # required)

